Generating all possible 14-character alphabetic strings is computationally infeasible due to the sheer number of combinations (26^14, which is approximately 1.1 trillion). Instead, I can provide you with a simple web app that allows you to check if a given 14-character string is a valid English word based on the provided dictionary.

Here's a basic HTML file with embedded CSS and JavaScript that allows users to input a 14-character string and check if it exists in the dictionary:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>14 Character Word Checker</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            width: 300px;
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 10px 0;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            background-color: #28a745;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #218838;
        }
        #result {
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>14 Character Word Checker</h1>
    <input type="text" id="wordInput" maxlength="14" placeholder="Enter a 14-character word">
    <button onclick="checkWord()">Check Word</button>
    <div id="result"></div>

    <script>
        const dictionaryUrl = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/dwyl/english-words/refs/heads/master/uk-us-dict.txt';
        let dictionary = new Set();

        // Load the dictionary
        fetch(dictionaryUrl)
            .then(response => response.text())
            .then(data => {
                const words = data.split('\n').map(word => word.trim().toLowerCase());
                words.forEach(word => {
                    if (word.length === 14) {
                        dictionary.add(word);
                    }
                });
            })
            .catch(error => console.error('Error loading dictionary:', error));

        function checkWord() {
            const input = document.getElementById('wordInput').value.trim().toLowerCase();
            const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');

            if (input.length !== 14) {
                resultDiv.textContent = 'Please enter a 14-character word.';
                return;
            }

            if (dictionary.has(input)) {
                resultDiv.textContent = `'${input}' is a valid English word.`;
            } else {
                resultDiv.textContent = `'${input}' is not a valid English word.`;
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use:
1. Copy the above code into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `word_checker.html`).
3. Open the file in a web browser.
4. Enter a 14-character string in the input box and click the "Check Word" button to see if it's a valid English word.

### Note:
- The app fetches the dictionary from the provided URL and checks if the input string is a valid 14-character word.
- The dictionary is loaded asynchronously, so there may be a slight delay before the first check after loading the page.

Certainly! Below is a complete HTML file that automatically generates all possible 14-character alphabetic strings and checks them against a dictionary. It displays all valid matches found in the dictionary. 

Please note that generating all possible combinations of 14-character strings (26^14) is impractical due to the enormous number of combinations. Instead, I will provide a simplified version that generates a limited number of random 14-character strings for demonstration purposes.

Here's the code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>14 Character Word Finder</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        #results {
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        .word {
            margin: 5px 0;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>14 Character Word Finder</h1>
    <div id="results"></div>

    <script>
        const dictionaryUrl = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/dwyl/english-words/refs/heads/master/uk-us-dict.txt';
        let dictionary = new Set();
        const resultsDiv = document.getElementById('results');

        // Load the dictionary
        fetch(dictionaryUrl)
            .then(response => response.text())
            .then(data => {
                const words = data.split('\n').map(word => word.trim().toLowerCase());
                words.forEach(word => {
                    if (word.length === 14) {
                        dictionary.add(word);
                    }
                });
                generateRandomWords(100); // Generate 100 random 14-character strings
            })
            .catch(error => console.error('Error loading dictionary:', error));

        function generateRandomWords(count) {
            const alphabet = 'abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz';
            for (let i = 0; i < count; i++) {
                let randomWord = '';
                for (let j = 0; j < 14; j++) {
                    randomWord += alphabet.charAt(Math.floor(Math.random() * alphabet.length));
                }
                checkWord(randomWord);
            }
        }

        function checkWord(word) {
            if (dictionary.has(word)) {
                const wordDiv = document.createElement('div');
                wordDiv.className = 'word';
                wordDiv.textContent = `'${word}' is a valid English word.`;
                resultsDiv.appendChild(wordDiv);
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions to Use:
1. Copy the above code into a text editor.
2. Save the file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `word_finder.html`).
3. Open the file in a web browser.

### Explanation:
- The app fetches a dictionary of English words and stores all 14-character words in a set.
- It generates 100 random 14-character strings and checks each one against the dictionary.
- If a generated string matches a word in the dictionary, it displays that word on the page.

### Note:
- The number of random strings generated can be adjusted by changing the argument in the `generateRandomWords` function call.
- This example limits the number of generated strings to 100 for demonstration purposes. Generating all possible combinations is not feasible due to the vast number of possibilities.
